posts.name: Eli Barnett
posts.cooked:
The signal is smoothed, so it loses sharp peaks and (more importantly) is delayed relative to actual motion.

This can render velocity feedback useless.

posts.name: Brendan Simons, 5406
posts.cooked: Honestly, in this game, precise speed control isn’t important.  Unless battery life is your issue, shoot every note at (a bit less than) your full speed, regardless of distance.  The Note will travel with less arc, and be more accurate .

posts.name: Eli Barnett
posts.cooked:
If your shooter wears over time (say grit gets in a bearing, or gear friction changes), feedback can make the difference between continuing to make shots late into a competition, and not.

It is always a good idea to have a safety factor and spare motor power in your design.  Without feedback, you can’t take full advantage of them.

posts.name: Andrew Schreiber
posts.cooked: With low inertia wheels you can get passable performance. But when I say low inertia I mean almost 0. And even then we had a bear of a time dialing it in.

Low inertia will make the performance worse when bad filtering is used and is not passable performance in the slightest. Low inertia flywheels can respond fast relative to the latency (or even faster) resulting in massive overshoot followed by violent oscillations caused by subsequent over-corrections pretty much making feedback control almost impossible.

posts.name: Andrew Schreiber
posts.cooked: You may be mathematically correct, and yet it was how we got somewhat stable performance.  I won’t be trying with higher MOI wheels, or ideally with neos/sparkmaxes any more.
